description.text: This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/f4T5sWqltyq

I call this thing the N_struder. With this revision being an N = 2struder. The original design intent was to hack http://www.thingiverse.com/jag awesome http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:7113 for use with my cupcake, but after seeing Makerbot's MK7 I ended up taking it to a whole new level. Design Concepts:
Cooling Fan: I mostly wanted to use parts and stock I have laying around my shop. The idea with the location of the heatsink is to cool the stepper motor (while still using a MK3 geared DC motor I noticed after long builds the filament would strip). I fixed this with a vacuum pump blowing air right on the hobbed drive, keeping the motor cool to the touch (a terrible solution), but it worked. With this location it also allows for any cooling fan to be attached. I think it is important to have a large heatsink, like a CPU fan when using multiple extruder heads. I imagine 100W+ possibly which is in the range for a CPU fan (plus they are often found FREE!) Filament Drive/ Material Change:
The idea here is to only use (1) stepper motor and motor driver because I am too cheap :). But really I think this method may prove useful.
Basically there will be a servo that engages/ disengages each filament through linkages (not in design yet). Then driving the stepper CW for one, then CCW for the latter. When disengaged the filament is pulled away from hobbed drive.
I have found using a 180 degree servo you get a few extra degrees allowing the mechanism to lock (like locking your knee or elbow), enabling the need for no power, with only the small exception of material change. Added Benefits:
This was designed with extruder head spacing of only 12mm (more build area).
Less cost and more simple. no need for two sets of motors, drivers, housings, ect...
Use of 1.75mm stock
Expandable to many heads (see N = 4struder concept). Well that was a mouthfull. But I have a question for the thingiverse hivemind. Is there an interest in implementing something like this?
I have no programming knowledge so it's useless to me without help.
I will continue designing the servo driven version if anyone thinks it's a good idea.
Also, other suggestions would be helpful.

Publish Early/ Publish Often?
This is a major work in progress. After I build the first one I will post all files.
I uploaded the whole assembly if anyone wants to take a look.
If anyone wants another file type just ask.
You may notice there is no "engaging arm" on the left. That's because Alibre does not have a mirror function(FAIL), but I will find a way to work around that somehow.

description.text: A friend of mine at work needed a Kinect TV Mount; I wanted it to be snug so I added a gripping mechanism that is spring loaded. If I get a few request I will add adjustments for a wii sensor and a playstation eye to mount as well. Thanks Please like it if you make it! So I know if other people are using it.

I printed out the base, which I had to flip upsided down because the STL is designed funny. After which I printed the two arms in one print.
Using .20 mm layers and 20% in-fill. Assembly is easy; clean off support material the scissor arms slide inbetween each other and then slide the bolt through the top of the mount down through the scissor arms and fasten the bolt. Next attach a small spring to the two arms using a paper clip or small screw. I used screws but they where randomly selected. The holes are around .125 mm It requires at least a 2 inche #4 bolt and nut, two small screws or wire to fasten the spring.. And a 1.8 inche spring. you could use a shorter one for more tension.

title: 2020 V Rail Hexagon Hot End Carriage Dual Fan BLTouch Mount V1

description.text:
If you make one, please show us! Especially the dual hot end version please! Cobblebot desperately needs a better hotend mount with fans and probe mounts. Here is version 1 I am working on based on the one made by satoer's E3D V5 hotend carriage. I really like this design and hope others will be able to use it, not just on the Cobblebot but any printer using 2020 rails should be able to use it. It uses the FelixE3DV5[fanduct[V2 (why reinvent the wheel?) but the heat sink doors were completely made from scratch around the hexagon. BLTouch mount has been tested successfully. My Z offset was 1.5mm. Your mileage may vary. There are 3 BLTouch mounts of varying heights available to download. THIS THING IS FUNCTIONAL AT THIS POINT. I have finished printing all the pieces and am now actively printing with it. The doors are very tight on the heat sink and will probably need to be heated enough to do a final form fit around yours. UPDATE 2016/01/29: New carriage for dual extruder. No probe attachment. (yet) Use M4 bolds and nuts to fit together. Use a piece of wire hangar for the hinge pin. Cobblebot users: You will be able to mount the wheels from the original carriage onto this. UPDATE 2016/03/24: Carriage V3_B moves the wheels across the rails 1.5mm closer together. The carriage should not be loose. I found V2 for me was just on, but the wheels wore down so that I couldn't make it tight enough. V3 fixes this. UDATE 2016/04/05: I have put the BLTouch mount A back on and a new C also. Each one differs from the other by 1mm with the tallest to shortest being B, A, C respectively; in the case you have a longer/shorter pin or some other variation requires it. BLTouch Configuration in Marlin v1.1.0-RC2 (there are changes in 1.1.0-RC4 Z probing that I haven't worked out yet. This config won't work on it. The print head will crash.) Get the BLTOUCH HERE: http://store.timeshell.ca/index.php?route=product/product&product_id=50 Here is a link for guidance on getting the firmware to save the new autoleveling matrix:
http://3dprintboard.com/showthread.php?8064-Saving-G29-Bed-Level-Correction-Matrix-to-EEPROM In Configuration.h: 1. Invert Z min
  • const bool Z_MIN_ENDSTOP_INVERTING = false;
    • 2. Enable servo and set endstop angles to the S codes provided by BLTouch:
  • #define NUM_SERVOS 3
  • #define Z_ENDSTOP_SERVO_NR 0
  • #define SERVO_ENDSTOP_ANGLES {{0,0}, {0,0}, {10,90}}
    • 3. Enable AUTO_BED_LEVELING_FEATURE and Z_SAFE_HOMING:
  • #define AUTO_BED_LEVELING_FEATURE // Delete the comment to enable (remove // at the start of the line)
  • #define Z_SAFE_HOMING
  • // Set these appropriately for the size of your printer
  • // These are set for my Cobblebot basic
  • #define LEFT_PROBE_BED_POSITION 15
  • #define RIGHT_PROBE_BED_POSITION 250
  • #define FRONT_PROBE_BED_POSITION 20
  • #define BACK_PROBE_BED_POSITION 250
  • // Set the number of grid points per dimension.
  • // You probably don't need more than 3 (squared=9).
  • #define AUTO_BED_LEVELING_GRID_POINTS 4
    • 4. Check your BLTouch sensor offset to your extruder!! (These settings are for the Cobblebot Hotend Mount by Irononreverse on thingiverse)
  • #define X_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER -39 // Z probe to nozzle X offset: -left +right
  • #define Y_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER -22 // Z probe to nozzle Y offset: -front +behind
  • #define Z_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER -1.6 // Z probe to nozzle Z offset: -below (always!)

Notes: I print with a 0.4mm nozzle. And although I haven't done so, I believe I'd also recommend printing in ABS. So far I'm only printing in PLA but it seems to be holding up. I've printed a few things in ABS with it without any apparent problems. 22 hours into a print at 210°C and the PLA built version still going strong. Incidentally, I tried making the carriage with ABS. I found the door mount to be very weak and broke easily. The PLA version seems to be much stronger. Your mileage may vary.




I recommend slicing with a thickness of 0.12mm, especially for the TS2020DoorMount.




Infill Recommendations:

TS2020Carriage 100%

TS2020DoorMount 15% or higher

TS2020DoorOpen 15% or higher

Fan Duct ?

TS2020Accessory 15% or higher

Right now I have to reheat the finished blocks with a heat gun to soften them to final form them around the heat sink as it is a very tight fit.  I'm hoping to adjust the design enough that this won't be necessary.
I found an STL file of the hexagon hot end.  I built blocks in 123D Design and subtracted the hexagon from them.  Then I created shapes and subtracted them as necessary to create the form needed.

For a long time I have struggled to get my Delta endstops right and bed leveled. Then my lab bought UM2 printer which had this rather nice bed levelling system with springs and I thought it would be rad if could level my Delta same way.

I planned to use my purple hexagon shaped heated bed as a levelling platform, it even had holes in the right places. I printed out six pairs platform supports and thumbwheels (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:641854). From one of my previous project I happened to have a assortiment of springs (form ebay: http://goo.gl/2nZCJ9) where I got suitable springs to support the platform.
For fixing mounts to the heated bed I had to use common M3 bolts, nuts and washers, mainly because the holes in the purple hexagonal heated bed were about that size and I did not want to drill them to bigger size.
And finally you will need 6X M4 bolts and nuts for mounting it to the printer frame.

When everything was assembled and mounted on the printer I found out the harsh truth - heated bed does not slide very well with the threaded M3 bolts and gets often stuck. That caused some bending of the pcb (heated bed) so the outcome was even more distorted heated bed. So I scrapped the project and moved back to old heated bed holders.
Future perspective would be to design this thing with only three levelling points and hope it would work better. Some time later I discovered this amazing webpage which makes levelling your Delta a piece of cake even without any bed levelling option: http://escher3d.com/pages/wizards/wizarddelta.php

title: SOPORTE CARRETE FILAMENTO GRADUABLE (ADJUSTABLE FILAMENT SPOOL HOLDER)

description.text:
Base para bobinas de filamento graduable en amplitud de bobina desde 4cm hasta 13 cm lo que cubre casi todas las existentes.
El soporte de ejes puede colocarse en ambos sentidos para usar tornillos de M3 o M4 tipo cabeza cilíndrica allen o cabeza alomada ranurada, según necesidad y tipo de rodamiento seleccionado ( los rodamientos pueden ser los del eje "Y" de la P3STEEL ). En el centro tiene capacidad para una tuerca del anclaje a las bases pero no es necesario ya que el diseño mantiene el tornillo apretado sin problemas.
Las bases se unen al soporte de ejes con 2 tornillos M3x20 o M3x25 cabeza cilíndrica "allen".
Se incluye un suplemento para la base que aunque no es necesario alza la pieza 4mm y permite utilizar otros tornillos de fijación en este caso M3*25 cabeza alomada ranurada.
El tornillo de apriete es M4x20 con cabeza hexagonal para que quede fijo a la base inferior ( colocar con calor ).
El cabezal de apriete ( maneta ) esta diseñado para albergar dos tuercas M4 que han de colocarse con calor ( dos tuercas proporcionan mas apriete) o una tuerca M4 con autofreno, y una arandela para que el apriete sea más firme.
Si al conjunto se le colocan 4 topes de goma se obtiene mejor firmeza y menos deslizamientos sobre mesas muy lisas.

Video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PqW18kimKDQ The Delta Hover Extruder combines the advantages of bowden driven delta printers (fast speed and low weight hotend-base/effector) and the advantages of direct drive extruders (no oozing/no needless material). The extruder is hovering about 140mm above the hotend. This shorter distance between extruder and effector decreases the friction and increases the direct traction enormously. With the standard retraction setting of 2-3mm I got no oozing and every time the correct amount of material! The extruder is centered between the carriages (connected with rubber-band or springs). To reduce the additional weight I have installed a counterweight on the Z-tower connected with a cord and 2 bearings like an elevator. The influence of the additonal weight is nearly zero.

description.header: This system is compatible with nearly every existing delta printer bowden extruder!

description.text:
1x Any existing bowden extruder for your delta printer, I'm using the extruder from schlotzz http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:275593
1x bearing 8mm inner diameter
1x bearing 5mm inner diameter
1x threated rod M8 (length depending on your printer size)
4x M8 Nut for threated rod
1x M5 Screw and Nut for small bearing
1x long cord or flexible filament (length depending on your printer size)
1x some springs or rubber band(s)

• Print the Delta Hover Extruder parts from here
    a) 1x Delta Hover Extruder Roof
    b) 1x X-Attachment
    c) 1x Y-Attachment
    d) 1x Z-Attachment
    e) 1x (optional) bearing case for the rod or use 2 flat washer
    f) 1x (optional) counter weight container or use a bag filled with the same mass of the extruder :)

  • Assembling:
    a) Fix the Delta Hover Extruder roof part with cable ties on the motor of the extruder
    b) Place the extruder in the middle above the hotend and connect it with rubber bands or springs to the carriages. Later you have to find out the right length and material of these elements to decrease the vibration of the whole system and to prevent the oscillation of the extruder on fast speed.
    c) Mount the Bearing in the middle of the threaded rod (with flat washer or the optional bearing case) and fix the rod with the X and Y Attachments on the printer frame with screws or cable ties, that the counterweight cord on bearing will vertically align with the cord attachment of the Delta Hover Extruder roof part.
    d) Mount the Bearing on the Z Attachment and the attachment on the frame at the z tower end.
    e) Find any counter weight equaling the extruder (I'm using an additional NEMA motor in a bag). Connect the Delta Hover Extruder and the counterweight with the cord. Check the balance of the extruder and the counter weight by moving the system up and down.
    f) Cut off the bowden on the right length that the extruder is about 10mm below the level of the carriages.
    g) Connect the Delta Hover Extruder and the Hotend with the bowden
    h) Happy printing without ugly oozing !!! :)
    • Additional you can print my Flex-Filament Adapter http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1338205 if you want to prevent problems printing flexible filaments. If you have designed your customized or universal Z Attachment plz let me know.

title: Spool Holder Dust Cover for hopefully every Spool size

description.text:
Was needing the Spool Holder (wanted to have a dust proof enclosure) fitting for a Spool with a smaller Hole Diameter and wider width, still I wanted to be able to as well put the 200mm Spools in the same enclosure. I recreated the Shells and the Clips on my own (on the Design of "SPANNERHANDS" -> http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:994813), also added a Adapter for it to be mounted on the back of my 3D printer. How to do:
Print the original "Threaded Shaft" with a scale of 58% in X and Y and 140% in Z direction. For the original "Threaded Screw" I used 57% in X and Y and 140% in Z direction. The original "Locking Ring" I scaled to 58% in every direction (here I had a really tight fit). Now it comes to the Parts as I had been creating them. To my created Parts: "SpulenhalterClips" are the Clips to keep the Shells together. 6x needed.
"Spulenhalter" represents the Shell and has to be printed 5 times.
"SpulenhalterLoch" is the Shell with the hole for the Filament to go out and a 6mm Tubing to be connected.
"AdapterCTC" is the part that needs to go between the "Locking Ring" and the "Threaded Screw" for fixing the whole thing on the back of my (maybe your) printer. *It could be, that the parts might not fit on first try and you have to sand them down a little since I don't know your printer.
For mine it worked. Any suggestions or Questions?: Leave a comment.

title: Second and Third Iteration Sierpinski Tetrahedra

description.text: The Sierpinski Tetrahedron is the 3D analogue of the Sierpinski Gasket, a famous 2D fractal created by beginning with a triangle and removing triangles of increasingly smaller size. A true Sierpinski Tetrahedron has zero volume, because an infinite number of smaller and smaller tetrahedra have been removed.

The Sierpinski Tetrahedron can be created either by putting many other tetrahedra together, or by starting with a base tetrahedron and removing progressively smaller tetrahedra. I created this model by arranging tetrahedra in lower iteration Sierpinski Tetrahedra to form a higher iteration model. The edges were then expanded so there would be enough overlap among individual tetrahedra for printing. Iteration 1 Iteration 2 Solidified Iteration 2

Print it out, put the inset inside, and depending on the orientation of the inset, it can hold cups from small to large with ease.  For the largest of steins or liters of soda - simply remove the inset.  
For boat use, attach some of the tacky foam no-slip pads to the underside of the base.  It'll keep your drink secure.  In my car, a touch of Velcro on the base keeps it stuck to the carpet.  
Enjoy!

I printed mine in PLA - works great.  
It's ugly and simple - but I really grew to appreciate it's function.
